### How Environment Feeds Back on Man — The Concept of Environmental Feedback

This is where the syllabus becomes deeply important for JRF. The environment is not passive. When humans disturb it, it responds — and those responses come back to affect humans.

These responses are called **feedback loops**, and there are two types:

A negative feedback loop resists change and stabilises the system. Example: forests absorb CO₂ and cool the atmosphere — this is a natural check on warming. When CO₂ rises, plants grow faster and absorb more — partially dampening the rise.

A positive feedback loop amplifies change and destabilises the system. Example: Arctic ice melts due to warming → less white ice means less sunlight reflected back to space → more heat absorbed by dark ocean → more warming → more ice melts. This is a runaway spiral.

For NET/JRF, positive feedbacks in climate change are critically important: permafrost thaw releasing methane, ice-albedo feedback, and Amazon dieback are three you must know.

