### The Concept of Carrying Capacity in Human Context

The Earth has a finite capacity to support life. This limit is called the **carrying capacity** (K). For human beings, carrying capacity is not just about food — it includes water, energy, clean air, and the environment's ability to absorb waste.

When a human population and its technology demand more from the environment than it can regenerate, it is called **ecological overshoot**. The Earth Overshoot Day concept measures this — in recent years, humanity uses up the Earth's annual resource budget by around late July, meaning we borrow from future years for the rest of the calendar year.

---

### Environmental Determinism vs. Possibilism — A Classic NET Theme

Two major schools of thought describe the Earth–Man relationship:

**Environmental Determinism** (older view, 19th century geographers like Ellsworth Huntington) argues that the physical environment controls human culture, behaviour, and development. Tropical climates make people "lazy," temperate climates drive "progress" — this view is now discredited as it was used to justify colonialism. But the kernel of truth is that environment sets real limits.

**Environmental Possibilism** (newer view, Paul Vidal de la Blache) argues that humans are not determined by environment — instead, nature offers possibilities, and culture decides which possibilities to use. Humans can farm deserts with irrigation, live in Arctic cold with technology, build cities on floodplains with engineering.

**Neo-Determinism / Stop and Go Determinism** (Griffith Taylor) is a middle path — yes, humans have freedom of choice, but certain choices are much harder or cheaper than others because of physical geography. You can build a city in a desert, but it will always cost more water and energy than a city near a river.

UGC NET questions frequently test which view is associated with which geographer.

