### Ecosystem Services — The Economic Language of Earth–Man Interaction

One powerful modern framework for understanding what Earth and environment provide to humans is **ecosystem services**, defined by the Millennium Ecosystem Assessment (MEA, 2005). There are four categories:

**Provisioning services** — the products ecosystems produce: food, fresh water, timber, fibre, genetic resources, medicines.

**Regulating services** — the benefits from regulation of ecosystem processes: climate regulation, flood control, disease control, water purification, pollination.

**Cultural services** — non-material benefits: recreation, spiritual value, aesthetic value, education.

**Supporting services** — the base services that enable all others: nutrient cycling, soil formation, primary production (photosynthesis).

When humans degrade an ecosystem, they are withdrawing from this natural capital account. The Millennium Ecosystem Assessment estimated that 60% of global ecosystem services were being degraded or used unsustainably.

---

### Concept of Anthropocene — High Priority for JRF

The term **Anthropocene** was popularised by atmospheric chemist Paul Crutzen in 2000 (though biologist Eugene Stoermer used it earlier). It proposes that since around the mid-20th century, human activity has become the dominant driver of changes to the Earth system — comparable to geological forces.

Key markers of the Anthropocene: rapid increase in CO₂ and methane; accelerating biodiversity loss (sixth mass extinction); novel materials in rock strata (plastics, concrete, artificial radionuclides); nitrogen and phosphorus cycle disruption; large-scale land use change.

The formal geologic body (International Commission on Stratigraphy) has debated but not yet formally ratified the term, but it is scientifically widely accepted.

